The decision sheet — picking the right gold object. This is the whole module compressed onto one page: you read the scenario, you pick the object.

Heavy aggregation that B-I dashboards refresh many times an hour — materialized view. Continuous fact ingestion, where the gold table should reflect a live stream — streaming table. A light wrapper, hiding P-I-I columns, or encoding a common filter — a plain view. A full declarative pipeline with quality gates, lineage, and C-D-C — Lakeflow Spark Declarative Pipelines. S-C-D type two history on a dimension fed by C-D-C — apply-changes-into, stored as S-C-D type two. Drop rows that fail a quality rule but keep the pipeline going — expect-or-drop. Stop the pipeline on a critical violation — expect-or-fail. Reject bad rows at write time on a plain Delta table — a check constraint. And custom batch logic you control end to end — a plain Delta table written by a Lakeflow Jobs task.

Now, if you remember nothing else, remember three tells that unlock most of these questions. One: "reads it a lot, refresh on a schedule" points to a materialized view. Two: "arrives continuously" points to a streaming table. Three: "keep full history of changes" points to apply-changes with S-C-D type two.

And everything else is really a variation on three fallbacks. A view — the cheap logical wrapper. A check constraint — the write-time guard on plain Delta. And expectations — pipeline data quality, chosen by severity: expect to track, expect-or-drop to filter, expect-or-fail to stop. Hold those three tells and three fallbacks, and the modeling questions on this exam become almost mechanical.
